\begin_layout Subsection
General Conservation Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
In Integral Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a connected 
\noun on
domain
\noun default
 in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
density
\noun default
 of some physical quantity, i.e.
 something per unit volume.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
flux
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 how much 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 leaves 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 through its surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 in unit time per unit area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $j(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
source
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 how much 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 generates in unit time per unit volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the 
\noun on
conservation law
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\dv{t}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}=\int_{V}j(\phi)\dd{V}-\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{f}(\phi)\dd{S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 is moving with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}^{B}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{t}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}=\int_{V}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}-\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\phi\vec{v}^{B}\dd{S}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
In Differential Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth with respect to spatial variables, we can apply Gauss's divergence
 theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{B}\right)\dd{S}=\int_{V}\div(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{B})\dd{V}
\]

\end_inset

Then, the conservation law can be written in the differential form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{B})=j(\phi)
\]

\end_inset

However, if the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth prerequisite is not satisfied, we should go back to the integral
 form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discontinuity Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a discontinuity surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 moving with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}^{S}=\vu{e}_{\perp}V_{\perp}^{S}+\vu{e}_{\parallel}V_{\parallel}^{S}
\]

\end_inset

Choose such a cylindrical control volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
with an infinitesimal height, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\vec{v}^{B}=\vec{v}^{S}\qc\lim_{h\to0}\int_{V}\dd{V}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
all the walls are 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp S$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the top 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) and the bottom 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=-\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\parallel S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sandwiched inside 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the conservation law contains surface integrals only
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{S}\right)\dd{S}=\int_{S_{+}\cup S_{-}}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\vec{f}(\phi)-\phi\vec{v}^{S}\right)\dd{S}
\]

\end_inset

Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and take the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\pm}:=\int_{S_{\pm}}\dd{S}$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{V_{\perp}^{S}=\frac{f_{+}-f_{-}}{\phi_{+}-\phi_{-}}\qc f_{\pm}=\lim_{h\to\pm0}\vu{e}_{\perp}\cdot\vec{f}}
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\noun on
Rankineâ€“Hugoniot condition
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Linear Advection Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
As a Conservation Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest initial-value problem (IVP) is the first-order partial differential
 equation (PDE) with constant coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0\qc t>0\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset

with the initial condition (IC)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t=0,x)=u_{0}(x)\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PDE only make sense in smooth regions.
 However, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:=u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}:=\vu{e}_{x}au$
\end_inset

, we can formulate it as a conservation law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characteristic Curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a\implies x=at+x_{0}
\]

\end_inset

is a one-parameter family of parallel curves in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 plane, with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 as the parameter.
 Such curves are called the 
\noun on
characteristic curves
\noun default
 of the PDE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Along characteristic curves, the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{u}{t}=\pdv{u}{t}+\dv{x}{t}\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

which means 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 remains constant along characteristic curves.
 The 
\noun on
general solution
\noun default
 of the IVP is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u_{0}(x_{0})=u_{0}(x-at)
\]

\end_inset

The physical meaning of this solution is a wave packet moving with constant
 speed 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, whose shape remains unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Riemann Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the IC is given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{0}(x)=\begin{cases}
u_{-} & x<0\\
u_{+} & x>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{+}$
\end_inset

 are two constant values, it defines a Riemann problem.
 The solution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u_{0}(x-at)=\begin{cases}
u_{-} & x-at<0\\
u_{+} & x-at>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Note that on the discontinuity, the PDE does not make sense; instead, the
 Rankine-Hugoniot condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\frac{au_{+}-au_{-}}{u_{+}-u_{-}}\equiv\frac{f_{+}-f_{-}}{\phi_{+}-\phi_{-}}
\]

\end_inset

is satisfied.
\end_layout

